</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-gvZzpm chTUkt pf-61_ pf-heading-1-h3"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-fmzxHC hSXinz pf-63_">Cellular-Level Damage
















</span></h2><p class="sc-bfhwqR jqvVoJ pf-64_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-fmzxHC hSXinz pf-66_"><strong><a href="https://www.ellenmacarthurfoundation.org/a-new-textiles-economy" target="_blank"><span style="color: rgb(196, 135, 74);"></span></a></strong>At a cellular level, inhaled microfibers trigger inflammation and oxidative stress. Laboratory-grown <strong>"mini lungs" </strong>exposed to nylon microfibers showed <strong><a href="https://www.rug.nl/news/2025/04/microplastics-and-their-effects-on-the-human-body?lang=en" target="_blank"><span style="color: rgb(196, 135, 74);">disrupted cell differentiation</span></a></strong>, impairing the lung’s ability to regenerate tissue after damage [8].












 







<strong>
</strong>









<br>

</span></p><p class="sc-bfhwqR jqvVoJ pf-67_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-fmzxHC hSXinz pf-69_"><strong><a href="https://www.ellenmacarthurfoundation.org/a-new-textiles-economy" target="_blank"><span style="color: rgb(196, 135, 74);"></span></a></strong>Animal studies reinforce these concerns: mice exposed to tire-derived microplastics developed fibrotic lesions in their lungs and chronic inflammation, similar to what is seen in early stages of interstitial lung diseases [9].













 







<strong>
</strong>









<br>

</span></p><p class="sc-bfhwqR jqvVoJ pf-70_ pf-text-1" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-fmzxHC hSXinz pf-72_">Additional studies in 2024 confirmed that persistent exposure to synthetic particles results in <strong>oxidative damage to lung cells</strong>, contributing to long-term respiratory conditions [10].















 










